AIM
To implement regular expression module 

Algorithm:
Step 1:Import the re module.
Step 2:Define a source string (text) containing an email and a phone number.
Step 3:Match at start: Use re.match() to check if the string begins with a specific pattern.
Step 4:Search anywhere: Use re.search() to find the first occurrence of a 10-digit number.
Step 5:Find all: Use re.findall() to extract all substrings that match an email pattern.
Step 6:Iterate matches: Use re.finditer() to locate the content and start position of matches within the string.
Step 7:Substitute: Use re.sub() to replace all digits in the string with an asterisk (*).
Step 8:Split: Use re.split() to break the string into a list using whitespace as the delimiter.
Step 9:Validate Full Match: * Take a date input from the user.
Step 10:Define a pattern for DD/MM/YYYY.
Step 11:Use re.fullmatch() to verify if the entire input string strictly follows the format.
Step 12:Display all results and outputs.

Code
import re

text = "My email is tanya@gmail.com and phone is 9876543210"
pattern_match = r"My"
match_result = re.match(pattern_match, text)

if match_result:
    print("1. match():", match_result.group())
else:
    print("No match")

pattern_search = r"\d{10}"
search_result = re.search(pattern_search, text)

if search_result:
    print("2. search():", search_result.group())
else:
    print("Not found")

pattern_findall = r"\w+@\w+\.\w+"
findall_result = re.findall(pattern_findall, text)
print("3. findall():", findall_result)

print("4. finditer():")
for match in re.finditer(pattern_findall, text):
    print(f"Found: {match.group()} at position {match.start()}")

pattern_sub = r"\d"
sub_result = re.sub(pattern_sub, "*", text)
print("5. sub():", sub_result)

pattern_split = r"\s"
split_result = re.split(pattern_split, text)
print("6. split():", split_result)

date = input("Enter date (DD/MM/YYYY): ")
date_pattern = r'^\d{2}/\d{2}/\d{4}$'

if re.fullmatch(date_pattern, date):
    print("Valid date format")
else:
    print("Invalid date format")

